   I, Suraqis, have here created a lod of the wonders and perils
of this mountain city Eriosthe.  In it I have left my thoughts
and reflections which may be of help to you who read this.
   The lord Uukrul has cast a pall of darkness across our land.
It shames me to think he was once of our calling.  Now, twisted
and ruined by promises of corruption, he mocks at us; but his
arrogance will be his downfall.
   Uukrul, fearing another attack by the Council, has hidden his
black heart in a magical chalice, protected by six locks.  Each
may be opened by a petrified human heart.
   In the caverns hidden by web of teleporters is a pool: a pool
of tears.  Within the pool lies a small black rod.  If this rod
is taken to the beacon, the beacon can be lit.
   Uukrul's agents have hidden two hearts west of the caverns.  I
know not where they are, but have heard tell that one lies with
the dead.
   The dark lord has warped the passages where he finally
defeated the valiant Mara.  She was forced to flee to the west
and these passages, cursed and corrupted, now hide another heart.
   Uukrul commanded a dragon to guard one of the hearts, but the
drake of diamond took the darklord's words and twisted them into
a game of his own choosing.
   The mirror within the diamonds carries the promise of
Eriosthe's future.  Uukrul has cast a dark vision upon it which
portends only doom.  The fair image must be awakened, though I
know not how.
   The urn that hides the black heart lies behind an accursed
maze of shifting walls.  The heart holds the magic that lets the
dark lord leave this plane he can appear and vanish at will.
   Uukrul constructed a prison from the pyramid.  Only those
possessing magical cards could move between its levels.  The
warders held and tortured many of Eriosthe's truest hearts. Some
who were with Mara fell here.
   There are control rooms above the great underground river.
These regulate the machines of Eriosthe.  If they were
ever destroyed Eriosthe could be crippled.
   The carriageway which spans the mountain range is powered by
the river.  It is the only passage connecting east to west, and
can be operated by a single spoken word.
   Uukrul and his minions now occupy the great palace of the god
Adron that lies at the eastern side of Eriosthe.  He has twisted
its purpose to his own dark ends, and laid chaos beyong its
halls. ...
